The paper deals with linear-algebraic objects such as subspaces, linear maps, and codes, which are typically studied in information theory (cs.IT), data structures (cs.DS), computational geometry (cs.CG), computational complexity (cs.CC), and machine learning (cs.LG). The focus on subspace designs and rank-metric codes also suggests a connection to coding theory, which is a subfield of information theory. Additionally, the use of tensoring and dimension expanders suggests a connection to computational geometry and complexity theory.
